            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the smell of stale coffee and ozone from the server racks in 2001. His staff was gone, the office dark but for his monitor\u2019s glow. Outside, the great bonfire of the dot-com era was collapsing into embers. He ignored the panic, methodically highlighting lines on a spreadsheet, making the brutal, unpopular call to cut a promising but cash-burning project. It wasn't a victory, but a cold, grim survival. That night, he learned that sometimes winning meant being the last one standing, a lesson that became his creed.\n\n2.\nHe was home in Grand Rapids for Christmas, shortly after getting his acceptance to Kellogg in the mid-90s. Standing on his parents' porch, he watched neighbors shovel their driveways in a familiar, rhythmic pattern. He could see his entire future laid out on that street\u2014a safe, respectable, and suffocatingly straight line. Clutching the acceptance letter in his pocket, he felt not just ambition, but a desperate, gasping need for escape. San Francisco wasn't a destination yet; it was simply *not this*.\n\n3.\nIt was their final conversation as husband and wife, around 2014, conducted over the cold marble of their kitchen island. There was no shouting, just the quiet finality of a contract being dissolved. When she said, \"You didn\u2019t build a life with me, Stephen, you built a portfolio,\" the words didn't sting with anger, but with the quiet, devastating accuracy of a market analysis. He nodded, accepting the emotional cost he had long since written off. The distance he felt was the price of his ambition.\n\n4.\nLast fall, taking his daughter to dinner near UCLA. He chose a sterile, acclaimed restaurant he\u2019d read about. He tried to connect, asking about her five-year plan, a conversation framework he knew well. Her polite, one-word answers across the table felt like miles of empty space. The silence on the pristine ride back to her dorm was deafening. For the first time, he felt utterly unqualified for the one merger that mattered most. The void he felt wasn't financial; it was paternal.\n\n5.\nJust a few months ago, at a museum gala. He stood holding a glass of champagne, half-listening to a banking CEO, when he saw his reflection in the darkened glass of a display case. He didn't see a successful man. He saw a man in a rented costume, perfectly positioned, perfectly isolated. The city\u2019s vibrant energy, which he\u2019d always admired from on high, felt for the first time like a party he wasn't truly invited to. The achievement felt complete, and completely empty."
